#: ../../source/Research.rst:29
msgid ""
"The light field in an optical cavity interacts with a mechanical "
"resonator via radiation pressure. In a typical setup, the cavity has one "
"moving end-mirror which constitutes the mechanical degree of freedom. "
"When the mechanical position varies, the cavity length changes which "
"modifies its resonance frequency. On the other hand, when adding more "
"photons in the cavity, the radiation pressure on the mirror increases, "
"which shifts the resonator's rest position. This optomechanical coupling "
"gives a high degree of control on the dynamics of the mechanical "
"resonator through the cavity, making it possible to use this platform for"
" applications such as ground state cooling, sensing or quantum "
"manipulations of the mechanics. It also makes it of great interest for "
"thermodynamics: work and entropy measurements, heat engines proposals, "
"..."
msgstr ""

